3-node cluster → quorum = 2 (majority), do we require qdisk arbitration or onlye fencing is sufficient

Short answer: You do NOT need qdisk in a 3-node PCS cluster. Fencing (STONITH) is sufficient and mandatory.

🧠 Why quorum works without qdisk
In a 3-node cluster:

Total votes = 3

Majority (quorum) = 2

So:

If 1 node fails → remaining 2 nodes still have quorum ✅

If network splits (1 vs 2) → the side with 2 nodes wins automatically ✅

👉 This already solves the split-brain problem without external arbitration.

🔥 Role of Fencing (STONITH)
Even with quorum, fencing is REQUIRED.

Why:

If a node becomes unresponsive but still running resources → risk of data corruption

Fencing ensures the faulty node is powered off before resources start elsewhere

✔ So in production:

pcs property set stonith-enabled=true
❓ When is qdisk needed?
QDevice (qdisk) is useful mainly in:

1. 2-node cluster
Votes = 2 → quorum = 2 ❌ problem

If 1 node fails → no quorum

Solution: add qdevice → total votes = 3 → quorum = 2 ✅

2. Special cases (rare)
Multi-site clusters (geo clusters)

You want an external tie-breaker

🚫 For your case (3-node cluster)
❌ qdisk / qdevice → NOT required

✅ fencing → MANDATORY

✅ quorum → already handled

⚠️ Best Practice Checklist
For a stable 3-node cluster:

✔ Fencing configured for all 3 nodes

✔ stonith-enabled=true

✔ No no-quorum-policy=ignore (avoid risky config)

Check:

pcs property show
🧾 Simple Conclusion
2-node cluster → need qdevice

3-node cluster → no qdevice needed

Fencing → always required (in both cases)

