In 3 node cluster, if i need my services to be running even if 2 nodes fails, then what we have to do

This is a very important design question — and the answer is a bit hard truth:

❗ Short Answer
In a 3-node cluster, if 2 nodes fail, you cannot keep services running safely using normal quorum rules.

🧠 Why this happens
In a 3-node cluster:

Total votes = 3

Quorum = 2 (majority)

If 2 nodes fail:
Only 1 node remains

Votes = 1 → ❌ No quorum

👉 Cluster will stop all resources (default behavior)

⚠️ Can we force it to run on 1 node?
Yes, but it is risky.

Option 1: Ignore quorum
pcs property set no-quorum-policy=ignore
What happens:
Single node will continue running resources ✅

But:

❌ Risk of split-brain

❌ Possible data corruption (especially for DB, shared storage)

👉 This is NOT recommended for production unless you fully understand the risk.

🔥 Safe & Recommended Approaches
✅ Option 2: Increase cluster size
Use 5 nodes instead of 3:

Votes = 5

Quorum = 3

Now:

If 2 nodes fail → 3 nodes remain → ✅ services continue

✅ Option 3: Use QDevice (better approach)
Add a qdevice (arbitrator node):

Total votes = 4 (3 nodes + 1 qdevice)

Quorum = 3

Now:

If 2 nodes fail:

1 node + qdevice = 2 votes → ❌ still not enough

👉 So even with qdevice, you still can’t survive 2 failures safely

✅ Option 4: Application-level HA (best for critical apps)
Instead of relying only on cluster:

Use DB replication (Oracle Data Guard, MySQL replication, etc.)

Use app-level failover

🚫 What NOT to do
Don’t rely on no-quorum-policy=ignore for critical systems

Don’t disable fencing to “force” availability

🧾 Final Conclusion
Requirement	Solution
Survive 1 node failure	✅ 3-node cluster
Survive 2 node failure	❌ Not possible safely with 3 nodes
Survive 2 node failure safely	✅ Minimum 5 nodes
👍 Practical Advice
If your requirement is:

“Service must run even if 2 nodes fail”

Then:

✔ Go for 5-node cluster

✔ Or redesign with replication + DR

